40|$|An entity has {{a foreign}} {{subsidiary}} operating {{in an economy}} that is considered highly inflationary for accounting purposes. Accordingly, the entity's <b>reporting</b> <b>currency</b> has been used as the subsidiary's functional currency in accordance with Statement 52. Except for inflation considerations, the subsidiary's functional currency would have been the local currency. Because of significant declines in the rate of inflation for the local currency in recent years, the foreign economy is no longer considered highly inflationary. The issue is how the entity should account for a change in its subsidiary's functional currency from the <b>reporting</b> <b>currency</b> to the local currency when the economy ceases to be considered highly inflationary. EITF DISCUSSION The Task Force reached a consensus that paragraph 46 of Statement 52 does not apply to this type of change and that the entity should restate the functional currency accounting bases of nonmonetary assets and liabilities at the date of change as follows: the <b>reporting</b> <b>currency</b> amounts at the date of change should be translated into the local currency at current exchange rates and those amounts should become the new functional currency accounting bases for the nonmonetary assets and liabilities. Exhibit 92 - 4 A illustrates the application of this consensus. Copyright © 1992, Financial Accounting Standards Board Not for redistribution Page 1 The Task Force also noted that the difference between the new functional currency basis and the functional currency tax basis represents a temporary difference under Statement 109 and the Task Force discussed how the related deferred taxes should be recognized. The Task Force was not asked to reach a consensus on this new issue, but requested that a separate Issue Summary be prepared for discussion at a future meeting. [Note: See STATUS section. ...|$|E
